pictures for dissemination to vast unseen audiences-and constitute it as something that can be bought, owned, and sold. With an impressive command of broadcast history, as well as critical and cultural studies of the media, Streeter shows that liberal marketplace principles-ideas of individuality, property, public interest, and markets-have come into contradiction with themselves. Commercial broadcasting is dependent on government privileges, and Streeter provides a searching critique of the political choices of corporate liberalism that shape our landscape of cultural property and electronic intangibles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBroadcasting policyzUnited States. 0aBroadcastingxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aBroadcastingzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226777290423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226777290.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles